You said:
How to choose between rest and message queue
ChatGPT said:

Thatâ€™s an excellent decision point ğŸ‘Œ â€” whether to use REST (synchronous) or a Message Queue (asynchronous) depends heavily on your business requirements and system design goals.

Hereâ€™s a breakdown to guide your choice:

ğŸ”¹ 1. Nature of Interaction

REST (Sync) â†’ Use when the caller expects an immediate response.
Example:

User clicks "Get Balance" â†’ API calls account service and returns instantly.

Message Queue (Async) â†’ Use when the response can be delayed or not needed.
Example:

User places an order â†’ Order service pushes "OrderCreated" event to queue â†’ Inventory, Payment, and Notification services consume independently.

ğŸ”¹ 2. Coupling

REST â†’ Tight coupling. Caller must know the service endpoint and wait.

Message Queue â†’ Loose coupling. Services communicate indirectly via a broker; publishers donâ€™t care who consumes.

ğŸ”¹ 3. Reliability & Fault Tolerance

REST â†’ If the target service is down, the request fails (unless you add retries, circuit breakers).

Message Queue â†’ Provides durability, retries, and buffering. Messages can be processed later if consumers are down.

ğŸ”¹ 4. Performance

REST â†’ Good for low-latency, point-to-point calls. But under heavy load, caller can be blocked.

Message Queue â†’ Absorbs spikes (load leveling). Can handle very high throughput but adds latency (not real-time in milliseconds).

ğŸ”¹ 5. Complexity

REST â†’ Simpler to implement, debug, and monitor.

Message Queue â†’ Adds infra (Kafka/RabbitMQ/SQS), monitoring, and operational overhead.

ğŸ”¹ 6. Use Cases Table
Scenario	Best Fit
User needs immediate answer (login, balance check, fetching data)	âœ… REST
Service-to-service data query (user service asks profile service)	âœ… REST or gRPC
Event notification (order placed â†’ notify inventory, billing, email)	âœ… Message Queue
Decoupling multiple consumers (audit logs, analytics, fraud detection)	âœ… Message Queue
Load spikes expected (ticket booking, flash sales)	âœ… Message Queue
Simple, low traffic	âœ… REST

âœ… Rule of Thumb:

If the caller cannot proceed without the response â†’ REST.

If the work can happen later or multiple services may act on it â†’ Queue.

